node.text: Our door policy — first come, first served — has remained the same at D&C East Village since our opening on New Year's Eve 2006 until last year, when our bars closed their doors for what we hoped, at the time, would only be a few days or weeks. Once we were able to begin the reopening process, we instated reservations for the first time in our history; now, almost a year later, we've returned to full operations and are enjoying every moment in our dark, welcoming space. Additionally, we've returned to our original door policy — we encourage you to stop by and if there's a wait, we'll take your name and number and let you know as soon as there's an opening at the bar. Thank you for your continued support and understanding; we couldn't do any of this without you. See you soon! (📷: @ericmedsker)

node.text: @matthewsbelanger's Melonball at Death & Co LA features an oft-overlooked fruit as a key ingredient: cantaloupe. Clarified cantaloupe juice is force carbonated to create a slightly sweet, flavorful addition to the cocktail's base of Suntory Toki Japanese Whisky and Hidalgo Oloroso Sherry. The resulting cocktail is light, bright, and, in our opinion, restores the reputation of the well-deserving cantaloupe. Try it on your next visit to D&C LA. (📷: @meetjakob)

node.text: There's a rhythm behind the bar that comes with busy evenings. Every movement is intentional, every step thoughtfully calculated. However, there's also a kind of magic within that rhythm that alights on certain nights — where everything feels easy, effortless, right. Not every evening is one of those, but the nights where the stars align just so make every challenge worth it. (📷: @shawnxcampbell)

node.text: Today is National Daiquiri Day, and while we're never in need of a particular reason to enjoy a daiquiri, we're using today as an excuse to try one of our favorite projects — experimenting with the cocktail's balance. A daiquiri’s balance is found through the collaboration between citrus and sugar and there is some flexibility in the amount of each depending on your preferences for tart or sweet. For our Goldilocks experiment to test where your preferences for sweet and sour fall, you'll need a shaker, jigger, cocktail strainer, three chilled coupes, ice, 2.5 oz of fresh lime juice, 2 oz of simple syrup, and, of course, a bottle of rum. For the purposes of this experiment, we forgo the garnish in order to keep the focus on the sweet-tart balance in the cocktail itself. Head to our Instagram stories for the step-by-step and let us know where you net out in the end. Cheers! (📷: @dylanandjeni)

Congratulations are in order for Javelle Taft, D&C East Village's new Head Bartender!⁠
⁠
Javelle (@javelletaft) started his career at Death & Co just over four years ago, beginning as a barback and splitting his time between D&C, Dutch Kills, and bartending at our sister bar, @nitecapnyc. With a focus on personal growth and education, Javelle quickly built a strong circle of mentors and friends while deepening his passion for crafting cocktails. He’s now the first barback in our history to work up to head bartender. Javelle’s inspiration typically stems from sharing meals with loved ones, his current favorite ingredient is Sherry (of any expression!), and when not at the bar, you can typically find him chasing endorphins cycling or adventuring outdoors. ⁠
⁠
Join us in congratulating Javelle on his new position — we’re incredibly lucky to have him on our team. (📷: @ericmedsker)

Join us this Thursday, July 15 at D&C East Village for Head Bartender Shannon Tebay's last shift at Death & Co.⁠
⁠
Shannon's (@shannontebay) history at Death & Co spans over a decade; she first joined us at D&C in 2010 as a server and then again as a bartender in 2017. Over the years, Shannon has done much more than make drinks. She's built strong teams, facilitated wedding proposals and baby gender reveals, and forged fiercely loyal and close friendships. Of course, let us not forget the drinks; each cocktail Shannon debuted, each menu she oversaw was finely-tuned to nothing short of enjoyable excellence. She brings a meticulous eye and boundless creativity (and, often, her favorite ingredient: coconut) to every single thing she does. As Shannon embarks on her next incredible journey, we wish her the absolute best — we know she never settles for anything less.⁠
⁠
Shannon's last night at the bar is this Thursday, so stop by and join us in congratulating and raising a glass to the inimitable Shannon Tebay. Thank you, Shannon, for everything! (📷: @ericmedsker)

With peach season comes Peaches and Smoke season. According to our tagged photos here on Instagram, @apday's low-ABV Sidecar riff has been one of your go-to cocktails from Cocktail Codex as of late, and with good reason — the drink is both sessionable and seasonal. In Peaches and Smoke, the core is split between a larger portion of fortified wine and a small measure of strong spirit, the strong spirit then working with a flavorful liqueur (here, @giffardusa's Creme de Peche) to balance and season the cocktail. If you haven't already, try it at home with Alex's recipe below. (📸: @dylanandjeni)⁠
⁠
1 peach wedge⁠
1.5 oz Lillet rosé⁠
0.5 oz Pierre Ferrand Ambre Cognac⁠
1 tsp Laphroaig 10-year scotch⁠
0.75 oz @giffardusa Crème de Pêche⁠
0.75 oz fresh lemon juice⁠
0.25 oz simple syrup⁠
Garnish: 1 peach wedge⁠
In a shaker, muddle the peach. Add the remaining ingredients and shake with ice, then double strain into a chilled coupe. Garnish with the peach wedge.

node.text: On-the-go breakfasts — bacon, egg, and cheeses, smoothies, a cup of black coffee — serve a specific function: getting one from point A to point B. We appreciate their utility and will rarely turn them down. But, when leisure allows, very little beats a proper sit-down breakfast. Luckily for us (and for you!), DC/AM is built for both kinds of mornings: simple, delicious, and quick or hearty, relaxed, and unhurried. Join us seven days a week for whatever early start your day calls for. See you soon! (📷: @shawnxcampbell)
